Karl (Carl) Leonard Nilsson (Nelson)

Carl Leonard Nelson: An Immigrant's Journey of Faith and Resilience

Born Karl Leonard Nilsson on April 16, 1894, in Veinge (or Weinge), Halland, Sweden, Carl's life began in the rural setting of the family homestead in Mestocka. The son of Nils Peter Andersson and Kristina Plsdotter, his original surname, Nilsson, reflected the Scandinavian patronymic tradition (the child's last name was based on the father's first name). Karl completed the 7th grade in school. Standing at 57, he grew up likely immersed in the Lutheran faith, the dominant religion in Sweden. The political unrest in Europe, leading to the outbreak of World War I, likely fueled Carl's desire to seek a new life in America. Just after his 20th birthday, he embarked on a nine-day journey aboard the RMS Alaunia, departing from Southampton, UK, and arriving in Portland, Maine, on April 19, 1914. Carls early years in the United States were tumultuous. The onset of World War I, just months after his arrival, and the devastating 1918-1919 influenza pandemic, which claimed thousands of lives in Rhode Island, deeply impacted Carl. Given his strong spiritual beliefs, it is likely he viewed the pandemic as a divine act. When he came to the US, he could not speak English and he learned to Speak and understand English by looking at the pictures and words in the Sears Roebuck catalogue. He would have people help him say the words that went with the pictures. Carl likely worked a number of odd jobs after coming to America. One year he worked as a cranberry bog worker in Massachusetts. He worked in the cold weather and the men where given a shack to live in which they shared with a slop bucket for toileting and a bucket of water to drink and to wash up. The water would freeze making it unusable and some of the men's ears froze and had frostbite and turned black. The frostbite was very painful and the men suffered. It was a very hard job but he made it through the season. Carl believed he was very strong and that is why he made it through this difficult work experience in addition to that God watched over him. Carl was very resourceful and committed to bettering himself so he could succeed in the US. He felt it was important to try to lose his accent (which he never completely did) because in the factories where we worked, Swedish men were considered to be "dumb swedes". He read the bible regularly and was an avid listener to religious programming on the radio which helped his English. Around 1919, Carl found employment at Samuel Moore & Company, a Providence jewelry manufacturer located near 301 Friendship St. This building, now on the National Register of Historic Places, was a testament to the company's significant role in the jewelry industry. Carl worked as a wire roller, a skill he would hone for over four decades. In 1923, Carl returned to Sweden to bring his sister, Signe, to America. They sailed from Christiania (now Oslo, Norway) on the SS Frederik VIII, arriving in New York on December 1, 1923. At 29, Carl, now Nelson, was the guide for his 21-year-old sister, Signe Nilsson, who spoke only Swedish. They planned to stay with Mrs. J. Sipples at 159 Pound St, Providence. Carl's spiritual journey led him to join the Church of Jesus in 1926, attending services at a hall on 7 Winter Street, a short walk from his workplace. On September 20, 1927, he became a naturalized citizen as Carl Leonard Nelson, residing at 159 Pound St. In 1928 at the age of 34, he married Evelyn Dodge, who was 17 years of age and the daughter of the churchs minister. In 1930, the couple moved in with the Dodge family, following Mrs. Dodges belief that God wanted them to live together. According to the 1930 census, they resided in a tenement at 770 Westminster St, Providence, alongside other church members.
1929 - 1939 were the years of the Great Depression and undoubtedly was a difficult time for many of the church members. In 1936, Carl made a $100 down payment on a small house at 222 Crescent Ave, in Cranston, believing he would have a share in it. However, the title was placed solely in the names of Fred E. and Mabel C. Dodge. In 1937, Amos Bray, a church brother, purchased three lots on Crescent Avenue for a larger house. In 1938, Carl invested $9,876.25 (equivalent to approximately $200,000 in 2025) into the construction of the big house at 196 Crescent Avenue, again with no ownership share. The 1940 census revealed 16 people living in the home, including the Dodge and Nelson families. On June 9, 1947, the church, led by Mrs. Dodge, eectively evicted Carl and his family, leaving them homeless. Carl pursued legal action, and in 1949, he won a landmark case, Nelson v. Dodge, receiving $10,468.82 in damages. This case set a precedent against undue influence by churches over parishioners' finances. With these funds, Carl purchased his lifetime home at 215 Garden Street in the Eden park area of Cranston, the Swedish community in this area was sometimes humorously referred to as Sweden Park. Until the day he died, he never lost his faith in God when that could have easily happened. He never once said a bad word about any of the church home people and never once came across as being bitter about the situation. He never talked about the situation at all. He had a strength of character to be able to rise above what was an extremely traumatic situation for the family and get on with his life in a way where his faith in God remained first. It must have been so hard because his path would cross with church home people who were family and others he considered to be friends after they left the church home where these people had testified against him in court. I can only imagine what he felt when they testified against him and what he felt after they left. It would have been so understandable if he spent the rest of his life a bitter man, but he didn't.
DETAILS OF COURT CASE 1948DETAILS OF APPEAL 1949 Carl took pride in keeping his body healthy and strong. He rode his bike instead of driving whenever he could and never drank alcohol feeling that the body was a gift from God. he often quoted Psalms 90:10 "The days of our years are threescore years and ten; and if by reason of strength they be fourscore years". Carl loved nature and tended a large garden in his yard including fruit trees. He enjoyed the ocen shore and felt that salt water had healing properties. The 1950 census showed Carl, 54, working as a jeweler, and Evelyn, 39, as a delicatessen saleswoman, living with their five children.
After their children reached adulthood, Carl and Evelyn moved upstairs, renting the first floor to their daughter Ruth and her family. Eventually his daughter Ruth purchased the home next door and her daughter Miriam lived just a few doors down the street. Carl retired in 1961 after 42 years at Samuel Moore & Company. In November 1978, Carl and Evelyn celebrated their 50th wedding anniversary, surrounded by 180 relatives and friends. At that time, they had five children, 16 grandchildren, and six great-grandchildren. Mayor-elect Edward DiPrete presented them with a proclamation from Mayor Taft of Cranston. Known for his close relationship with his children, his financial prudence, and his daily bike rides, Carl was also deeply spiritual, engaging in long prayers when called upon at family gatherings. He eventually moved to the Scandinavian Home in Cranston due to declining health. Carl Nelson passed away on April 5, 1986, at the age of 91, leaving behind a legacy of resilience, faith, and family. His life story is a testament to the immigrant experience and the strength of the human spirit.
